<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS -- Bookshelf:
   Subcontinental Snapshots
   ----
   By Lee Lescaze
</HL>
<DATE>
12/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7
</SO>
<LP>
   The first time V.S. Naipaul went to India, in 1962, he was
just 30 years old, a writer not yet famous, not yet
financially secure.
   His trip resulted in "An Area of Darkness," a dazzling
travel book of acute observation and sharp-edged comment,
colored by the shock and disappointment that the
Trinidad-born writer felt in the country of his ancestors. In
a nation that many Westerners and even greater numbers of
privileged Indians believed possessed of a spiritual light
deserving respect from less-enlightened parts of the world,
Mr. Naipaul found darkness. The book outraged those devotees
of the cult of India's spiritual superiority -- all the more
so because it awakened others to the prevalence of cant and
cruelty in the land of Gandhi and Nehru. The enormous impact
of "An Area of Darkness" greatly enhanced Mr. Naipaul's
reputation.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   That first encounter was much in Mr. Naipaul's thoughts
when he set out in 1988 on another long visit to India. His
timing was good because since independence in 1947 India has
never been so prosperous, nor so troubled. On the one hand,
India has left behind its early beggarly dependence and
created a large middle class that, in turn, is the engine of
a consumer-spending boom. On the other, violence is rising
from Kashmir to Assam and only the Soviet Union faces more
separatist challenges to central government control.
   It seems a perfect moment for Mr. Naipaul's latest report.
But, "India: A Million Mutinies Now" (Viking, 521 pages,
$24.95) disappoints. Mr. Naipaul is no longer a young writer
on a tight budget. He stays in the best hotels and travels
with hired car and driver. Something also has changed in Mr.
Naipaul's nonfiction.
   His new book on India follows "A Turn in the South," his
unoriginal, shallow look at the southern U.S. Mr. Naipaul now
seems uninclined to edit his material or allow others to do
so. As a result, the distinguished writer crams "India" with
overlong portraits of one Indian after another -- some
interesting, some not. Often he includes his questions as
well as the answers as though every word were important. At
its worst, "India" is like reading the transcripts of Bill
Moyers dialogues -- including the outtakes. It is earnest,
respectful, high-minded, but to no purpose.
   For almost four-fifths of this lengthy book, Mr. Naipaul
is content to keep his tape recorder running while his mind
idles. Once in a while he slips it into gear and, as one
would expect, out pops an arresting insight. But as he
travels through Bombay, Goa, Tamil Nadu and Calcutta he seems
determined not to explain what he thinks all his interviews
add up to.
   It's an old joke in journalism to hand an editor an
overlong story with the explanation: "I'm sorry, I didn't
have time to write it short." The point is that to write
short you have to know what your story is about. To write
clearly, you have to know what you think. For hundreds of
pages, Mr. Naipaul tempts the reader to conclude that he no
longer knows what he thinks about India.
   A murmur of apology runs through "India." The shock and
humiliation that the young Naipaul felt upon first
encountering the land that had long been so important in his
imagination has given way to a mellower view in the mind of
the middle-aged man. His youthful attitude he now calls "old
nerves" and seems to reproach himself for having been in 1962
"a fearful traveller." His disappointment, he writes now,
resulted from his having naively cherished "the idea of the
family of India." Indians didn't share such an illusion, he
knows now. The idea of an all-inclusive fellowship of man is
mocked daily in Indian life by caste, clan and religious
clashes.
   Today, Mr. Naipaul argues that the last 90 years of
British rule (after the mutiny) and the 40-plus years of
India's independence have been a time of regeneration in
which the idea of freedom has reached all Indians, bringing
self-awareness and strength.
   At last, when Mr. Naipaul reaches Lucknow, the Punjab and
Kashmir in the final sections of his book, he slips his mind
into gear and writes with some of the provocative keenness of
vision found in his earlier works. But his analysis leads him
to a dubiously wishful conclusion.
   Although separatist tendencies make headlines today, and
although India may not be the family of his youthful dreams,
he argues it has become a nation. The million little mutinies
of his subtitle are not cause for great alarm, only symptoms
of the rage that accompanies a liberation of the spirit, he
writes in words that would have saved him so many brickbats
had he written them in 1962. "The Indian Union was greater
than the sum of its parts; and many of these movements of
excess strengthened the Indian state, defining it as the
source of law and civility and reasonableness," he adds.
   The mutinies, like those in which Moslems and Hindus kill
each other in Kashmir or Sikhs and Hindus kill each other in
Punjab, are seen as a positive phenomenon: "They were part of
the beginning of a new way for many millions, part of India's
growth, part of its restoration."
   It would be nice to think Mr. Naipaul is right.
   ---
   Mr. Lescaze is the Journal's foreign editor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ901227-0101
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
901227-0101.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Retailing:
   After a Gray Christmas, Bleak Forecasts
   ----
   A Wall Street Journal News Roundup
</HL>
<DATE>
12/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<CO>
   S CMAFC NOBE KM TIF DESI T.CMP
</CO>
<IN>
ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)
BROADLINE RETAILERS, DEPARTMENT STORES (RTB)
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
SPECIALTY APPAREL RETAILERS (SAP)
SPECIALTY RETAILERS (OTS)
</IN>
<LP>
   The nation's merchants, spooked by the ghost of the bleak
Christmas just past, are bracing for tough times in the first
half of 1991.
   For bargain hunters, that is likely to mean a bonanza.
"We'll be more aggressive" in promoting special deals, vows
William McCarthy, president of marketing at Montgomery Ward &amp;
Co. in Chicago. Troubled Sears, Roebuck &amp; Co. also is
planning to tout more deals.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But some retail executives fear that, in the current
recessionary climate, even big price cuts won't coax
consumers to open their wallets. Just listen to Cari
Brookbanks, an advertising account supervisor in Chicago.
"I'm going to stay out of the stores," she declares, citing a
joint decision with her adman husband "to tighten our belts a
little bit."
   Says Linnette Peterson, a receptionist from Staten Island,
N.Y.: "I sure don't plan to get anywhere near the stores for
the January sales."
   Indeed, the retail slump shows no signs of abating after a
Christmas season that, by most accounts, finished on a blue
note. Despite widespread discounting, holiday sales slipped
below last year's at some stores while others barely exceeded
last year's receipts, industry executives say. After
adjusting for inflation, the final tallies for the crucial
holiday period are expected to be the worst in many years.
   The outlook for the first half of 1991 is even grimmer.
Consultant Walter Loeb predicts that same-store sales in the
first half of the year will decline as much as 4%, further
squeezing industry profits.
   "If the consumer wasn't shopping for Santa Claus and
Christmas, I can't imagine why they would shop in the first
half of the year," says Dayton Hudson Corp. Chairman Kenneth
Macke.
   "This is a difficult economic climate, and it makes
running the business a lot tougher," says Julian Taub, a
senior vice president at Campeau Corp.'s Bloomingdale's,
where holiday revenue was "within a percentage point or two
of last year."
   Predicts Jack McMillan, president of Nordstrom Inc.: "It's
going to be a tough first half."
   The wild card is the Persian Gulf crisis. The current
standoff undoubtedly depressed shoppers and contributed to
the slump in holiday sales. But "if war breaks out in the
Middle East, it could be catastrophic," says Arthur Martinez,
vice chairman of Investcorp International Inc.'s Saks Fifth
Avenue, which matched last year's holiday sales on a
same-store basis. "On the other hand, if the dispute is
favorably resolved, it could provide a psychological boost."
   In any case, most merchants are shrinking inventories,
cutting staff and expenses and planning to promote the sorts
of basic apparel and household products that typically sell
best in a recession.
   At K mart Corp., which registered a slight increase in
holiday sales, a spokesman says the discount chain is
"placing greater emphasis" on low-priced commodities such as
toothpaste, paper products and household cleaners, and
focusing less on more expensive televisions and stereo
equipment. "We're trying to put our inventories where we
think it will do us the most good," he says.
   The Christmas season provided ample evidence that
consumers, fearing a recession and a war, are trading down to
lower-priced goods and delaying discretionary purchases.
   At Bill's London Transit, a small men's store in Atlanta,
manager Philip M. Griffiths says shoppers tended to choose
$45 sweaters instead of $1,200 leather suits. Jerry Sheff,
owner of The Jewelry Store in Boston, says "customers stayed
away from anything costing $100 or more as if it were a
pickpocket." At FrontRunners Inc., a Los Angeles active
apparel retailer, owner Paul D. Tordella says he sold out of
T-shirts for the first time this December and socks were a
popular gift, even in the affluent neighborhood of Brentwood.
   Tiffany &amp; Co., while reporting a modest but lower than
expected sales increase at U.S. stores, says "the average
customer purchase declined somewhat." And a hot seller at the
Card Factory in Los Angeles was a new $55 model of the
Filofax datebook. Last year's big gift was a $99 Mont Blanc
pen, now priced at $115 and hardly moving.
   Designs Inc., a Boston-based chain carrying only basic
Levi Strauss &amp; Co. sportswear, posted a 23% increase in
same-store sales for the holiday period. "It could be an
indication that, these days, people are looking for the more
basic, steadfast product," says Samuel Levenson, assistant to
the company treasurer. The chain also discounted
aggressively.
   Some merchants blame the media for poisoning the Christmas
mood. "People have the money," insists Ami A. Peretz, who
owns the Vencci men's boutique in Los Angeles. "They're just
choosing not to spend it because the news caused people to be
concerned about the gift budget. By January or February, I
hope people will get a clearer picture of what's happening in
the world and start buying again."
   But consumers were singing a different tune. "This is a
scary, unpredictable time," says Kelly S. Fiand, a college
student and Los Angeles waitress who slashed her Christmas
budget to $200 from last year's $1,000. "People are worried
about the economy and war. . . . Customers just aren't
tipping the way they used to."
   Says Ms. Peterson, the Staten Island receptionist who
intends to stay out of the stores: "I'm kind of worried about
next year, since it's been downhill all the way on Wall
Street with so many folks getting laid off."
   Indeed, most retail industry executives have lowered their
expectations and changed their definition of success. "For a
while, if you weren't getting double-digit increases just by
opening the door, you weren't satisfied," says Robert M.
Benham, president of Hallmark Cards Inc.'s Halls and Swansons
department stores in Kansas City. "Now, I think it's
remarkable that most of us are running even, instead of off
10%. The whole perspective has changed."
   ---
                  Shoppers Take a Holiday
                                                                                                       

   How much did you shop this Christmas compared with last
year?
                                                                                                       

   Less often                            24%
   More often                            17
   The same as before                    58
   Don't know                             1
                                                                                                       

   Note: Based on a sampling of 400 people
   Source: MAS Marketing Inc.
                                                                                                       

   More than half of 450 households surveyed said they
planned to spend less this Christmas. Here are their reasons:
                                                                                                       

   Have less money                       50%
   Buying fewer gifts                    21
   Prices are too high                   12
   Spent too much last year              12
   Other                                  5
                                                                                                       

