<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial) -- Asides:
   Second Thoughts
</HL>
<DATE>
12/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<LP>
   Radio Liberty's Soviet/East European Report recently noted
a curious exchange between a leading Soviet philosopher,
Andranik Migranyan, and the eminent British philosopher Karl
Popper. About two years ago, some 100 Soviet philosophers
boycotted a speech to the World Congress of Philosophy by Mr.
Popper, author of "The Open Society and its Enemies." A year
before that speech, Mr. Migranyan made one of the earliest
calls for creating a genuine civil society in the Soviet
Union. Now, he told Mr. Popper in an interview, the country
needs an "iron hand" because "it's impossible to pass over
from totalitarianism to democracy at a moment's notice."
   No doubt some would sympathize with the notion that the
Soviet government has to regain control of its disorderly
society. However, it's difficult to understand Mr.
Migranyan's logic. The Soviet Union is disorderly because the
bureaucracy's thousands of iron hands won't let go of what
they once held. Giving them more "control" will likely choke
the newborn life out of Soviet civil society.
</LP>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ901227-0067
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
901227-0067.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   S&amp;P and CBOE
   Resolve Dispute
   On Licensing Pact
   ----
   By James P. Miller
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
12/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C17
</SO>
<CO>
   MHP
</CO>
<IN>
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
SECURITIES (SCR)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Standard &amp; Poor's Corp. and the Chicago Board
Options Exchange resolved a squabble over a licensing
arrangement covering S&amp;P stock indexes.
   S&amp;P, a unit of McGraw-Hill Inc., sued the CBOE in
November, charging the options exchange with breach of a
ten-year licensing pact, signed in 1983, under which the CBOE
was granted exclusive right to use the S&amp;P 100 and S&amp;P 500
indexes as the basis for exchange-traded options.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The CBOE, however, had recently been asserting that its
license to the indexes was broader.
   The dispute began last summer, when the underwriters
withdrew what was to have been an offering of $110 million in
five-year notes, at an interest rate linked to the
appreciation of the S&amp;P 500 index over the life of the bonds.
S&amp;P said at the time that the underwriters withdrew the
offering -- by the country of Denmark -- "apparently due to a
legal disagreement between S&amp;P and the CBOE" over whether the
Chicago exchange has the right to exclusively market any
security with a return based on movement of the indexes.
   S&amp;P and the CBOE said yesterday that they have "signed a
new agreement to extend CBOE's license to trade put and call
options" on the two stock indexes. In addition, they said
they have "agreed to terminate" the litigation that began in
November, under which S&amp;P asked the court to terminate the
1983 contract, or, alternatively, to rule that the pact
doesn't extend to financial instruments other than the
options spelled out in the original agreement.
   An S&amp;P spokeswoman said the new agreement extends CBOE's
rights to use the popular S&amp;P 500 index through 1998. As to
the exchange's perception that its license was broader than
that stated in the original pact, the "mutually satisfactory"
new agreement "did clarify" the relationship, she said. She
declined to elaborate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ901227-0066
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
901227-0066.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial):
   Lock In What With Whom?
</HL>
<DATE>
12/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<IN>
AEROSPACE (ARO)
NUCLEAR POWER, FUEL (NUK)
</IN>
<GV>
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
CONGRESS (CNG)
STATE DEPARTMENT (STD)
</GV>
<LP>
   Secretary of State Baker says Eduard Shevardnadze's
resignation shouldn't change U.S.-Soviet cooperation. With
the President scheduled to visit Moscow in February, U.S.
policy is to "lock in" arms-control agreements while the
Gorbachev era lasts.
   But the Shevardnadze resignation, it seems to us, raises
an even more fundamental question: With whom are we
negotiating? With the continued disintegration of the Soviet
Union, and with the collapse of President Gorbachev's de
facto authority even as he demands new paper authority, who
in the Soviet Union can order the Red Army to lay down its
arms?
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Recent events give us reason to doubt, indeed, whether
signing an agreement with Mr. Gorbachev can "lock in" the
current regime, let alone all future ones. In November, he
and President Bush signed a treaty paring back conventional
forces in Europe. But the ink was barely dry before the
Soviets began acting like there was no treaty at all. The
Soviets declared 20,000 fewer weapons than NATO thought they
had, and transferred others out of the area covered by the
treaty -- a clear treaty violation. By one account, the
Soviets literally replaced Army uniform patches with navy
markings, since naval "infantry" aren't covered by the
treaty.
   Even before November, one of the largest military
movements in history had already transferred some 60,000
tanks and armored pieces east of the Urals, where they also
won't be covered by the treaty. This may be technically legal
under the treaty, but it doesn't say much for the spirit of
disarmament. Instead of being destroyed along with NATO's
weapons, Soviet tanks will now sit just a few hundred miles
further east.
   The START nuclear-arms talks are also stymied, though
President Bush insists he wants to sign the treaty on his
February trip. The Soviets are balking at a U.S. request to
inspect plants for the rocket motors used to launch ballistic
missiles. These plants are easier for U.S. intelligence to
detect, so cheating would be more difficult. For their part,
the Soviets only want to allow inspection of missile-assembly
plants, which is like inspecting a house without looking at
the furnace. What do Soviet generals have to hide?
   This verification point is critical because the U.S. has
already agreed to the Soviet request not to ban mobile
missiles. In a country (or Russian republic) spanning 11 time
zones, there are plenty of places to stash warheads. Congress
is in the process of killing America's mobile missiles (the
MX and Midgetman), so any Soviet breakout would leave them
far ahead. Throw in concessions the U.S. has already made
limiting our best weapon, the cruise missile, and it's easy
to imagine a treaty that Georgia chameleon Sam Nunn could
pick apart in the Senate.
   And, amazingly, new SS-24 missiles (deployed on rail cars)
and SS-25s (on trucks) continue to roll off the assembly
line. The SS-25 made its first public appearance in a Kremlin
parade in November. Soviet military capabilities remain
formidable, and have continued to grow despite glasnost and
the rest. In particular, the Kremlin retains the world's
largest nuclear arsenal, with warheads still aimed at
Washington and Wyoming, not Baghdad. Leningrad citizens may
be clamoring for food, but the Soviet military seems to have
no problem getting what it needs. Indeed, the military
refuses to release or account for its own strategic food
reserves.
   All of which makes us wonder, what's our rush? So far,
arms control has not reduced the Soviet threat, even with Mr.
Shevardnadze, Mr. Gorbachev and the rest. It is even less
likely to restrain the Soviets if, as Mr. Shevardnadze fears,
its political system evolves back to "dictatorship." Indeed,
agreements may even retard Soviet reform by guaranteeing the
Soviet military a certain "floor" for its military
production. It's possible Mr. Baker wants a treaty for
American political purposes, of course, though it might prove
embarrassing to sign a treaty with a leader who turns around
and declares martial law in the Baltics.
   The Soviets are the ones who should be dying for arms
agreements, not us. They have the economy that's a shambles,
and the empire that's breaking at the seams. Why lock in
anything now? If we've really won the Cold War, why don't we
just declare victory in arms control, too?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
