<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
12/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   STOCKS AND BONDS rose on reports that Iraq and the U.S.
are preparing for talks. The 30-year Treasury bond gained
almost a point, pushing its yield down to 8.28%. The Dow
Jones Industrial Average ad vanced 15.84 points to 2637.13.
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Further interest-rate cuts are unlikely to result in a
broad, extended stock-market rally unless investors are
convinced that corporate profits will grow again, analysts
say.
   ---
   The retail slump shows no sign of abating after a
Christmas season that is believed to be the worst in many
years. Merchants expect tough times through the first half of
next year.
   ---
   Bank of New England bondholders said they won't approve a
proposed debt-for-equity swap unless they get assurances from
the government that the institution isn't about to be seized.
   ---
   Pan Am told TWA owner Icahn, in effect, to put up or shut
up in his effort to acquire Pan Am after he balked at putting
the bid into writing.
   ---
   Spending on research and product development is beginning
to taper off after more than doubling in the past decade.
Industry's share of such spending is projected to increase
2.2%, to $75.9 billion, next year.
   ---
   Citrus growers in central California are seeking
government disaster relief after a week of cold weather that
ravaged navel orange crops.
   ---
   Pennzoil raised its stake in Chevron to 9.4% from 9% by
acquiring 1.3 million shares for $89 million. Pennzoil also
said the IRS issued a favorable ruling regarding any further
such purchases made before May 31.
   ---
   Nissan's U.S. sales arm raised the base prices on its 1991
cars and trucks for the second time in four months. The
action reflects the weak dollar's pressure on the auto
maker's results.
   ---
   Donald Trump will run out of money to keep his operations
going unless he gets a cash infusion by mid-spring, his
advisers and bankers say.
   ---
   Short interest fell 2.3% among big OTC stocks in the
latest monthly period and 5.4% among smaller issues.
   ---
   McGraw-Hill's S&amp;P unit and the Chicago Board Options
Exchange settled a dispute over a licensing arrangement for
S&amp;P stock indexes.
   ---
   Grain futures rallied as indications of stability in the
Soviet Union eased traders' worries that the Bush
administration might not grant Moscow credit to purchase U.S.
crops.
   ---
   Tiffany's stock price tumbled $4.375 to $37.25 after the
jewelry retailer said earnings estimates for the current
fiscal quarter are too high.
   ---
   Tokyo stocks ended mixed in thin trading Wednesday as
concerns about the Mideast and the Soviet Union discouraged
participation by investors.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 78,730,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2637.13, up 15.84; transportation 922.23, up 1.32; utilities
211.33, up 0.63.
   Bonds: Lehman Brothers Treasury index 3654.03, up 26.45.
   Commodities: Oil $27.22 a barrel, up $1.30. Dow Jones
futures index 126.33, up 0.40; spot index 123.92, up 0.04.
   Dollar: 136.25 yen, up 0.25; 1.5368 marks, off 0.0072.
