<HL>
   SEC Examines Disclosures
   On A-12 Aircraft Finances
   ----
   A Wall Street Journal News Roundup
</HL>
<DATE>
12/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   MD GD
</CO>
<IN>
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<GV>
SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission is investigating
whether McDonnell Douglas Corp. and General Dynamics Corp.
have made proper financial disclosures regarding the troubled
A-12 aircraft program, both companies confirmed.
   Word of the SEC inquiry, which was first reported by
Defense Week, a trade publication, comes on the heels of a
separate criminal investigation into the A-12 project. That
probe is being led by the U.S. attorney in St. Louis, where
both companies are based.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney has given the contractors
until Wednesday to devise a plan to save the A-12, which
although designed to replace the Navy's aging fleet of A-6
attack planes, has been plagued by cost overruns, technical
snags and schedule slips.
   "The SEC has informed us that they are conducting an
informal inquiry related to our disclosures about and
accounting for the A-12 program," a McDonnell Douglas
spokesman said.
   A General Dynamics spokesman said the company is "aware
there's an investigation going on," but wouldn't comment
further. In Washington, an SEC spokesman declined comment.
   In the second quarter, General Dynamics registered a $450
million charge against earnings on the A-12, while McDonnell
Douglas used a different accounting method and didn't take a
writeoff. "We believe it's the difference in reporting that
led to the inquiry," the McDonnell Douglas spokesman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
