<HL>
   Law -- Legal Beat:
   Insurer Seeks Indemnity in Wickes Suit
   ----
   By Wade Lambert and Amy Dockser Marcus
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
12/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3
</SO>
<CO>
   WIX CIC PFE
</CO>
<IN>
LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)
SECURITIES (SCR)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
SECURITIES REGULATIONS AND ENFORCEMENTS (RGU)
INSURANCE (INS)
PROPERTY &amp; CASUALTY INSURANCE (INP)
MEDICAL SUPPLIES (MDS)
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   Continental Insurance Cos. asked a U.S. court to protect
it from having to pay Wickes Cos.' defense costs in
securities-fraud cases involving Michael Milken.
   Continental filed the lawsuit in federal court in
Manhattan asking the court to declare that Wickes's general
liability coverage doesn't apply either to defense costs or
any damages that might be awarded. Wickes is named as a
defendant, along with Mr. Milken and Drexel Burnham Lambert
Group Inc.'s brokerage unit, in four civil lawsuits alleging
securities fraud.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Continental argues that the insurance doesn't apply mainly
because the cases allege wrongdoing by Wickes. According to
the lawsuit, the coverage applies only to damages or injuries
caused by an accident. "Stock manipulation is the antithesis
of an accident," said Barry Ostrager, an attorney
representing Continental. "That's someone willfully
committing something that is wrong."
   The allegations against Wickes stem from stock
transactions in 1986 that allowed the company to convert its
preferred stock into nondividend-paying common shares and to
save about $15 million annually in dividend payments. The
lawsuits against Wickes, Mr. Milken and Drexel allege that
the conversion was the result of an illegal
stock-manipulation scheme. Prosecutors allege that Mr. Milken
directed the manipulation of the Wickes stock with the
assistance of Ivan Boesky; Wickes wasn't charged with any
criminal wrongdoing.
   A spokeswoman for Wickes, a Santa Monica, Calif.,
manufacturer and retailer, declined to comment on the suit by
the Continental Corp. unit.
   Both Mr. Milken and Mr. Boesky pleaded guilty to felonies
related to securities transactions, but the counts they
admitted didn't involve Wickes. Coincidentally, Continental's
lawsuit was assigned at random to Judge Kimba Wood, the same
judge who last month sentenced Mr. Milken to 10 years in
prison.
   ---
   PFIZER LOSES bid to throw out investors' suits over heart
valve.
   In federal court in Manhattan, Judge John Keenan rejected
a motion by Pfizer Inc. to dismiss the class-action lawsuits,
which seek unspecified damages. The lawsuits, which have been
consolidated, claim that investors from March 27, 1987, to
Feb. 26, 1990, were defrauded because Pfizer failed to
disclose problems with the artificial heart valve. On Feb.
26, a House subcommittee staff report criticized the New York
pharmaceutical company for its level of disclosure. The
heart-valve was removed from the market in 1986.
   Pfizer argued that the suits should be dismissed for not
making adequate claims of fraud. But Judge Keenan, in
allowing the suits to go forward, said: "The sources of
plaintiffs' allegations, such as the staff report and others,
are highly reputable. The allegations, therefore, are not
unfounded or speculative."
   Judge Keenan also said in his opinion that "Pfizer knew
that there were problems with the heart valves, and it knew
that suits {by heart-valve recipients} were being and
expected to be filed. Whether what was told to investors was
sufficient is an issue for trial."
   Attorneys for Pfizer couldn't be reached for comment.
   ---
   PROFESSOR WINS RIGHT to sue over alleged free speech
deprivation.
   A federal judge ruled that the professor, who espouses the
view that blacks are intellectually inferior to whites, can
sue officials of City College of the City University of New
York for allegedly violating his First Amendment right of
free speech.
   The professor, Michael Levin, who is white, teaches
philosophy at the college. His statements and writings about
race have led to protests and demonstrations at the school,
where the student body is 39% black, 28% Hispanic, 17% white
and 16% Asian. Following the campus protests, the college
formed a faculty committee to review the issue of when
academic freedom can be restricted and to examine some of Mr.
Levin's statements.
   Judge Kenneth Conboy ruled that because the committee's
recommendations could lead to the revocation of Mr. Levin's
tenure, the professor's suit can proceed. The judge didn't
rule on whether the college infringed on the professor's
rights. Mr. Levin said he has turned down speaking
engagements and requests for articles because he is worried
about how the faculty committee will react.
   In the suit, he also alleged that college officials were
unwilling to punish student protesters who disrupted his
classes and threatened his safety.
   ---
   MOST LIBEL CLAIMS against Glamour are thrown out in
Foretich case.
   A lawsuit by Eric A. Foretich alleged that a Glamour
magazine article left the false impression that he had
sexually abused his daughter, as claimed by his ex-wife,
Elizabeth Morgan.
   In throwing out all but one remaining libel claim, U.S.
District Judge Gerhard Gesell of Washington stated that it
was "crystal clear" that the disputed statements constituted
opinions and thus were constitutionally protected. Conde Nast
Publications Inc. publishes Glamour.
   The judge allowed Mr. Foretich to proceed with one libel
claim stemming from a reader's letter. A lawyer for Mr.
Foretich couldn't be reached for comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ901227-0018
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
901227-0018.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media -- Advertising:
   Agencies Foresee Unkinder, Rougher 1991
   ----
   By Joann S. Lublin
</HL>
<DATE>
12/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2
</SO>
<CO>
   ONE
</CO>
<IN>
ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)
</IN>
<LP>
   Forget about Eastern Europe, "personalized" marketing and
Japan's emergence as an international advertising force.
   Those hot topics on Madison Avenue during 1990 will move
to the back burner as we ring in the new year. The hottest
issue in 1991: surviving the "Big R."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Top ad agency executives, gazing into their crystal balls,
say the recession not only will slash companies' ad
expenditures and agency staff levels. It also will spark an
ad-industry crackdown on slow-paying clients, a rise in
client defections and an expansion of hard-sell marketing
techniques.
   "We're dealing with a very tough marketplace out there,"
says Carl Spielvogel, chairman of Backer Spielvogel Bates
Worldwide, a Saatchi &amp; Saatchi unit. Stanley Katz, chairman
and chief executive officer of Foote Cone &amp; Belding's New
York operation, concurs: "Everything is going to get tougher,
not better. If there's a danger sign ahead in 1991, it's an
overreaction to that" by agencies and clients.
   Here's how ad-industry leaders see the recession fallout
shaping up:
                                                                                                       

   Agencies will get tougher with their clients, curbing
generous credit terms for financially shaky companies and
shunning low-paying new accounts.
   During good times, agencies paid scant attention to how
slowly some clients paid their bills. No longer. With profit
margins squeezed, "agencies will watch their receivables like
they have never watched them before," says William Weithas,
chairman and chief executive of Lintas: Worldwide, an
Interpublic Group unit. "No businessman wants to take the
risk of doing business with either insolvent or low-rated
companies," he explains.
   For example, WPP Group's J. Walter Thompson relinquished
Health &amp; Tennis Corp.'s $50 million media account last month
after the unit of financially troubled Bally Manufacturing
refused to pay cash up front for media buys.
   In another sign of today's glum times, several major
agencies refused to bid for Trans World Airlines' $45 million
ad account this fall because the airline offered unusually
low compensation. Will agencies spurn TWA-type deals again?
"You can bet your life" they will, Mr. Weithas says. Ad
people "aren't going to give (their services) away."
                                                                                                       

   More jittery advertisers will dump their agencies,
snowballing this year's flurry of account switches.
   "Historically, more clients jump ship in bad times because
they get harder-nosed and say, `I want results,'" observes
Foote Cone's Mr. Katz.
   The greatest movement likely will come from industries in
the deepest trouble, such as retailing, financial services
and cars. Earlier this month, Montgomery Ward dropped Saffer
USA in favor of the Chicago office of D'Arcy Masius Benton &amp;
Bowles for its estimated $25 million to $30 million account.
Similarly, Chase Manhattan named Wells, Rich, Greene its lead
agency for more than $35 million in ad billings -- largely
forsaking Scali, McCabe, Sloves, the WPP Group unit that had
handled the majority of the account.
   Agency heads say they're hustling more aggressively for
new business because of the threat of defections and because
so many existing clients have trimmed their agency fees or ad
budgets.
                                                                                                       

   A stronger push for results will tilt the ad-spending
pendulum more toward promotions and spur advertisers to be
less daring in their campaigns.
   An expected slowdown in spending on coupons, contests,
sweepstakes and other short-term promotions never
materialized this year. Instead, companies worried about the
sour economy will keep shifting bucks away from traditional
media advertising because they can measure results faster
with promotions. Clients "feel they can't take any chances.
They need to get sales now," says Burton Manning, chairman of
J. Walter Thompson.
   Direct-mail expenditures, for example, should climb 6.5%
during 1991, a faster clip than any other ad category and
less than the scant 4.6% for all U.S. ad spending, predicts
Robert J. Coen, a McCann-Erickson senior vice president and
the ad industry's leading agency forecaster.
   The recession also will breed caution. Clients are
abandoning wildly creative ads and flighty corporate-image
drives in favor of "tried-and-true" techniques such as ads
focused on price cuts. "There will be a temptation to do a
lot more `me-too' advertising," notes JWT's Mr. Manning. He
and other agency chiefs find this strategy flawed. An
unexpected, startling or controversial ad is "the stuff that
sells the merchandise," he insists. But clients' interest in
unconventional approaches, he admits, "goes away in a
recession."
   ---
   Ad Notes. . . .
                                                                                                       

   STAFF MEETING: Banc One Corp. plans an unusual "staff
meeting," a 60-second spot to be aired on national TV on New
Year's morning. The Columbus, Ohio, bank holding company is
mailing memos to its 29,000 U.S. employees urging them to
tune in. During the ad, to be broadcast on CBS during the
Cotton Bowl Parade, Chairman and Chief Executive John B.
McCoy will discuss a new marketing effort. Details will come
Jan. 2 at the company's 747 offices. A Banc One spokesman
said the spot also may serve as a teaser for a related ad
campaign, scheduled to break at the end of January. Martin
Agency, Richmond, Va., created the ad.
                                                                                                       

   NEW ACCOUNT: The American Arbitration Association named
Alden Group, New York, to handle its new ad account. Billings
weren't disclosed. The New York-based association, which
mediates disputes, has done little advertising in the past.
</TEXT>
